In Controllers/ProTaskController.cs at line 7039, replace the untranslatable CLR shim with the EF-native nullable accessor that translates to SQL DATEADD:

  // before (L7039):
  endtime = (a.endtime < a.starttime) ? DbFunctionsCompat.AddDays(a.endtime, 1) : a.endtime

  // after:
  endtime = (a.endtime < a.starttime) ? a.endtime.Value.AddDays(1) : a.endtime

a.endtime is DateTime? (Models/ProTask.cs:35); .Value.AddDays(1) translates to DATEADD(day, 1, [endtime]) in EF Core 10 and is only evaluated in the branch where endtime < starttime (endtime non-null there). The false branch returns a.endtime so the ternary result stays DateTime?, preserving the downstream `.ToList().Select(... (o.endtime - o.starttime).Value ...)` arithmetic at L7049-7050. This exactly mirrors the legacy EF6 DbFunctions.AddDays(a.endtime, 1) at _archive/legacy-mvc5/Controllers/ProTaskController.cs:7452.
